df <- read.csv('data/mammal_hvy_metals_by_pop_withGUIDs.csv') %>%
  clean_names() %>%
  filter(!is.na(latitude) & !is.na(longitude))
# add in more data cleaning post mortem, once I understand what variables I am interested in

This dataset makes use of the University of Minnesotaâs Bell Museum of Natural History collection examining specimens of four mammal species (a mouse, shrew, bat and squirrel) to ask how tissue metal content has changed over a 94-year time period (1911-2005), and implications for measures of individual performance (body size and cranial capacity). The metal content of organisms is often elevated closer to cities, so these specimens were examined for spatial variation in metal exposure based on their proximity to human populations and the size of those populated areas at the time of collection. Analysis of mammal tissues focused on six heavy metals associated with human activity (Pb, Cd, Zn, Cu, Cr, Ni, Mn), to address whether these anthropogenic metal pollutants vary in concert with human activity.

Visualizations

# First data viz -> collections over time
df %>%
  mutate(mg_prop = mg/total_length) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = year_collected, y = mg_prop)) +
  geom_area(fill = "#e0e1dd") +
  geom_line(color = "#bde0fe") +
  theme_minimal() +
  labs(
    title = "Magnesium levels in mammal tissue over time",
    subtitle = "Mg level (ppm) is proportioned to animal size using length (mm)",
    x = "Year",
    y = "Mg Level",
    caption = "Data Source: Environmental Data Initiative (EDI), published May 28, 2024. \nCreators come from the University of Minnesota and The Minneapolis-St. Paul Long Term Ecological Research") +
  theme_ipsum() +
  theme(axis.title.x = element_blank())

# Third data viz -> sum magnesium levels by county
mg_df <- df %>%
  group_by(county) %>%
  mutate(total_mg = sum(mg)) %>%
  arrange(total_mg) %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  mutate(county = factor(county, levels = unique(county)))

ggplot(mg_df, aes(x = county, y = total_mg)) +
  geom_point() +
  coord_flip() +
  theme_minimal() +
  labs(
    title = "Magnesium levels (in mammal tissue) by county",
    y = "Total Mg"
  )
